WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.770
&gt;&gt; I myself have read Ramit's book, and I'll
tell you, as a finance major in college, I

00:00:04.770 --> 00:00:11.160
have not learned more about bank accounts
and credit cards than I can in four years.

00:00:11.160 --> 00:00:19.150
I learned it from Ramit more than college.
His book focuses on personal finance for people

00:00:19.150 --> 00:00:24.230
in their 20's and 30's, by weaving in together
threads from health and fitness, social psychology,

00:00:24.230 --> 00:00:29.089
and personal finance.
His blog, IWillTeachYouToBeRich.com, frequently

00:00:29.089 --> 00:00:35.700
crashes because so many people access it.
It hosts over 300,000 readers per month, and

00:00:35.700 --> 00:00:39.330
Ramit just told me he's getting new servers
to back up more readers.

00:00:39.330 --> 00:00:44.050
He's no stranger to Silicon Valley.
Previously, he cofounded a company called

00:00:44.050 --> 00:00:49.230
PBwiki, where he helped develop user acquisition
of millions of users.

00:00:49.230 --> 00:00:53.440
Ramit graduated from Stanford where he studied
technology and psychology.

00:00:53.440 --> 00:00:56.180
Please welcome Ramit Sethi.

00:00:56.180 --> 00:00:57.180
&gt;&gt; [applause]

00:00:57.180 --> 00:01:03.940
Ramit: Thank you very much. Testing one, two,
three.

00:01:03.940 --> 00:01:07.620
Ramit: Is this okay? Can you guys hear me?
Okay.

00:01:07.620 --> 00:01:14.940
Thank you very much for having me.
When I was doing my first start-up, we used

00:01:14.940 --> 00:01:21.430
to meet here about four times a week.
So thank you very much for that.

00:01:21.430 --> 00:01:27.250
Just a quick question.
Who here has read my blog or my book already?

00:01:27.250 --> 00:01:29.610
Okay.
Who here thinks it sounds like a big, fat

00:01:29.610 --> 00:01:32.340
scam?
"I will teach you to be rich" yeah.

00:01:32.340 --> 00:01:36.510
What I want to talk about today is a system
that I've been working on building for the

00:01:36.510 --> 00:01:41.540
last ten years.
And it comes down to, "Personal finance is

00:01:41.540 --> 00:01:45.440
not about willpower."
People think, "If I just try harder, I can

00:01:45.440 --> 00:01:46.960
save more money.
I can earn more money."

00:01:46.960 --> 00:01:51.330
Very similar to, "If I just try harder, I
can lose ten pounds."

00:01:51.330 --> 00:01:53.750
And clearly, it's more complex than trying
harder.

00:01:53.750 --> 00:01:57.770
It's clearly more complex than throwing tactic
after tactic out at people.

00:01:57.770 --> 00:02:03.140
What we're going to do today -- I want to
spend about a half an hour talking about the

00:02:03.140 --> 00:02:06.500
psychology of automation -- the psychology
of personal finance.

00:02:06.500 --> 00:02:09.469
And then, I'm going to talk to you a little
bit about the system -- how you can implement

00:02:09.469 --> 00:02:10.469
it today.
It takes about six weeks.

00:02:10.469 --> 00:02:12.920
People are pretty smart here, so you can probably
do it a little faster.

00:02:12.920 --> 00:02:18.549
And then, we'll just do a lot of Q and A.
I'd love to take questions.

00:02:18.549 --> 00:02:23.189
Personal finance is intensely psychological.
And, first of all, when I talk about, "I will

00:02:23.189 --> 00:02:26.629
teach you to be rich," I want to emphasize
that 'rich' is not just about money.

00:02:26.629 --> 00:02:31.450
For some people, 'rich' could mean buying
a Louis Vuitton bag or expensive shoes or

00:02:31.450 --> 00:02:34.071
traveling all the time.
That's perfectly fine. That could be a rich

00:02:34.071 --> 00:02:37.669
life to you.
For other people, it might be about charity

00:02:37.669 --> 00:02:40.370
or, you know, more traveling or whatever it
may be.

00:02:40.370 --> 00:02:43.829
That's fine too.
But 'rich' is only partly about money.

00:02:43.829 --> 00:02:49.400
The reason that I started this was, I got
sick and tired of personal finance experts

00:02:49.400 --> 00:02:55.689
telling us things like, "Don't spend money
on lattes," and "Keep a budget" -- which no

00:02:55.689 --> 00:03:01.749
one ever does, and is the most useless advice,
but continues to be expressed for the last

00:03:01.749 --> 00:03:04.150
50 years, even though no one keeps a budget.
It just doesn't work.

00:03:04.150 --> 00:03:06.499
So today, these are things we're not going
to talk about.

00:03:06.499 --> 00:03:09.129
We're not going to tell you to keep a budget.
I'm not going to lecture you about lattes.

00:03:09.129 --> 00:03:13.480
And for some reason, kooky people start talking
about Ron Paul and commodities when it comes

00:03:13.480 --> 00:03:15.499
to investing.
We're not going to talk about that either.

00:03:15.499 --> 00:03:19.909
What we are going to talk about is building
an automated system so that, by default, without

00:03:19.909 --> 00:03:21.549
trying, your money is doing the right thing,
okay?

00:03:21.549 --> 00:03:27.900
And that will let you lead a rich life and
spend your money guilt-free.

00:03:27.900 --> 00:03:34.169
Because 'I will teach you to be rich' is about
spending extravagantly on the things you love

00:03:34.169 --> 00:03:40.239
if you're cutting costs mercilessly on the
things you don't.

00:03:40.239 --> 00:03:41.290
So let's get to it.
In the next hour, we are going to go through

00:03:41.290 --> 00:03:44.790
a bullet-proof system.
This is a system that you can use for your

00:03:44.790 --> 00:03:47.590
own money.
And most people, if I ask you, "Where's your

00:03:47.590 --> 00:03:50.799
money going?" most people look at their bills
at the end of the month and go, "I don't know.

00:03:50.799 --> 00:03:54.819
I guess I spent that much."
I don't know why they talk like that, but

00:03:54.819 --> 00:03:58.599
they do.
Instead, what I'll propose is a bullet-proof

00:03:58.599 --> 00:04:02.870
system where, if I were to say to you, "Hey,
you need to start saving 500 bucks for this

00:04:02.870 --> 00:04:05.090
trip to Thailand you want to take."
You're going to say, "No problem.

00:04:05.090 --> 00:04:09.239
I know exactly where to take the money out
from here to here and have it flow over here.

00:04:09.239 --> 00:04:11.470
And it will be a couple clicks, and it will
be done -- automatically.

00:04:11.470 --> 00:04:13.370
We're also going to examine the psychology
of it.

00:04:13.370 --> 00:04:18.680
And I want to ask you guys to first take a
couple minutes with me to go deep into the

00:04:18.680 --> 00:04:25.889
psychology, because it's not just about tactics.
It's not about me telling you, "You need to

00:04:25.889 --> 00:04:26.889
spend less on this and earn more and do."
We know that.

00:04:26.889 --> 00:04:28.701
We know what we need to do. Why aren't we
doing it?

00:04:28.701 --> 00:04:34.080
I took a survey of about 1600 users and asked
them, "What are the things you wish you saved

00:04:34.080 --> 00:04:36.000
for 10 years ago?" And it was almost a uniform
curve.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:37.440
People in their 20's wished that they had
saved more for travel.

00:04:37.440 --> 00:04:45.039
People in their 30's wished that they had
saved more for their down payment on their

00:04:45.039 --> 00:04:48.110
house.
And people in their 40's were often really

00:04:48.110 --> 00:04:53.199
screwed if they haven't started -- wished
that they had saved more for their retirement.

00:04:53.199 --> 00:04:59.060
So we know what's going to happen to us ten
years from now, yet we delude ourselves into

00:04:59.060 --> 00:05:02.710
thinking, "We'll do it later."
I met a girl on my book tour. She's about

00:05:02.710 --> 00:05:05.629
25, 26.
And she told me a really interesting story.

00:05:05.629 --> 00:05:11.250
She said, "Ramit, I read your book, and I
started saving for my wedding.

00:05:11.250 --> 00:05:21.840
Already, I have a little sub-savings account."
I said, "Great, can I get this on flip cam?

00:05:21.840 --> 00:05:27.439
This would be awesome."
And she got very uncomfortable.

00:05:27.439 --> 00:05:35.440
She said, "No, no, no.
I don't want to talk about it on camera."

00:05:35.440 --> 00:05:42.340
I said, "Why?"
And she told me, "I'm not engaged yet." [laughter]

00:05:42.340 --> 00:05:57.069
Isn't it interesting that we know the average
age where a woman gets married, where a man

00:05:57.069 --> 00:06:04.880
gets married.
We know the average cost of a wedding.

00:06:04.880 --> 00:06:16.789
Put the numbers together, and it means that
if you're 20 years old, you need to be saving

00:06:16.789 --> 00:06:32.289
over $300 a month for your wedding.
If you're 25, over a thousand dollars a month.

00:06:32.289 --> 00:06:39.150
But who does this? It's so weird.
And it struck me, "Isn't it interesting that

00:06:39.150 --> 00:06:46.860
it's weird for this young woman in Portland
to be saving where it's actually normative

00:06:46.860 --> 00:06:50.550
for us to say, "Oh, I'll just figure that
out later."

00:06:50.550 --> 00:06:54.159
Or even more delusional, I'm just going to
have a small, simple wedding with a few friends.

00:06:54.159 --> 00:06:55.159
No, you're not. You're going to have a big-ass
wedding, because that's what we want.

00:06:55.159 --> 00:06:56.410
It's our day. So let's get real.
Let's be honest and acknowledge what the costs

00:06:56.410 --> 00:06:57.410
are going to be, okay?
There's also people who are even more delusional.

00:06:57.410 --> 00:06:58.410
Twenty percent of people actually believe
they'll get rich by winning the lottery. [laughter]

00:06:58.410 --> 00:06:59.410
I hate these people.
Ten percent think that they'll get rich through

00:06:59.410 --> 00:07:00.410
an inheritance.
I hate them as well.

00:07:00.410 --> 00:07:01.410
And perhaps, the most delusional of all.
Three percent via an insurance settlement.

00:07:01.410 --> 00:07:02.410
Yes, I'm sure -- smart three percent.
Not going to happen.

00:07:02.410 --> 00:07:03.410
Why don't we do this?
If I were to ask someone in their 40's, "What's

00:07:03.410 --> 00:07:04.410
the number one thing that you are worried
about or concerned about?" They would say,

00:07:04.410 --> 00:07:05.410
almost all of them, "Money."
We know it. We know we need to exercise more.

00:07:05.410 --> 00:07:06.410
We know we need to work out more, eat less,
and manage our money.

00:07:06.410 --> 00:07:07.410
Why don't we do it?
It's not about trying harder.

00:07:07.410 --> 00:07:08.410
That's something I want to emphasize today.
Let's take a look at some comparisons.

00:07:08.410 --> 00:07:09.410
When it comes to personal finance and food,
there's a lot of similarities.

00:07:09.410 --> 00:07:10.410
So the health and fitness world directly inform
your money behaviors.

00:07:10.410 --> 00:07:11.410
We spend more than we think.
We also eat more than we think.

00:07:11.410 --> 00:07:12.410
If you were to actually look and measure what
you ate, what you spent, you wouldn't like

00:07:12.410 --> 00:07:13.410
it.
You wouldn't tell people what you did.

00:07:13.410 --> 00:07:17.150
In fact, there's great research showing that
there were people who were more comfortable

00:07:17.150 --> 00:07:23.360
talking about their sex lives than their credit
card bills, making me ask, "Where do I find

00:07:23.360 --> 00:07:28.199
these people?" [laughter] Okay?
We value anecdotal stories over actual research.

00:07:28.199 --> 00:07:32.789
How many times have you heard your friends
say, "Oh, you really should invest in real

00:07:32.789 --> 00:07:36.320
estate -- it's the best investment." No, it's
not.

00:07:36.320 --> 00:07:39.550
Or you know, friends telling you, "the baby
minutiae."

00:07:39.550 --> 00:07:43.850
How many of you have heard friends saying,
"Don't eat fiber after 11 p.m., because it

00:07:43.850 --> 00:07:45.319
doesn't metabolize.
You need to eat fruit.

00:07:45.319 --> 00:07:50.560
But make sure you get your carbs in the morning"
 -- these weird theories that are not backed

00:07:50.560 --> 00:07:54.409
up with literature.
How many people do you know that complain

00:07:54.409 --> 00:08:00.449
about money but have never spent one weekend
actually optimizing their finances?

00:08:00.449 --> 00:08:03.199
You can do it once, and you can have the residual
benefits forever.

00:08:03.199 --> 00:08:08.060
So there are profound, psychological reasons
why we don't do what we know we need to do.

00:08:08.060 --> 00:08:11.449
We also have the media shoving down our throats
these ridiculous covers and ridiculous messages

00:08:11.449 --> 00:08:17.280
like, "Top ten stocks you must own in 2010."
Actually, analyze those media messages, and

00:08:17.280 --> 00:08:20.900
they are almost always wrong.
They don't even match the market.

00:08:20.900 --> 00:08:25.819
What they are doing is selling advertisements
and selling magazines, not selling good financial

00:08:25.819 --> 00:08:29.901
advice.
The answer is far more prosaic, and it's something

00:08:29.901 --> 00:08:33.060
I like to talk about which is, "Would you
rather be sexy or would you rather be rich?"

00:08:33.060 --> 00:08:37.530
Would you rather go to a party -- I'm a nerd.
I don't know if you guys do this, but when

00:08:37.530 --> 00:08:40.419
I go to parties, we talk investment strategy.
This is what we do.

00:08:40.419 --> 00:08:45.030
And people say, "What are you investing in?"
And it's sexy to say, "Well, I got this stock,

00:08:45.030 --> 00:08:48.390
and I'm looking at some early-stage angel
funding.

00:08:48.390 --> 00:08:51.661
Whereas the real individual investors are
simply saying, "Well, I picked an index fund,

00:08:51.661 --> 00:08:53.640
I got my asset allocation right.
It took me a weekend.

00:08:53.640 --> 00:08:55.960
And all I do is just automatically send money
every month.

00:08:55.960 --> 00:09:02.650
It's not as sexy, but it'll make you rich.
Other reasons -- and this is perhaps the most

00:09:02.650 --> 00:09:06.440
important of all.
There's just too much information.

00:09:06.440 --> 00:09:09.580
And everywhere we go, we've got our parents
who don't know anything about money, generally,

00:09:09.580 --> 00:09:11.370
telling us stuff.
We've got the media.

00:09:11.370 --> 00:09:14.500
We've got friends, who think they know, but
they don't really know.

00:09:14.500 --> 00:09:21.530
And we've got information all over the place.
What's the result of all this?

00:09:21.530 --> 00:09:26.690
It makes us actually want to do less.
It makes us -- when we see -- let's look at

00:09:26.690 --> 00:09:32.510
401k's, for example, great study in the the
book, The Paradox of Choice.

00:09:32.510 --> 00:09:37.590
When there are more options in your 401k,
people actually participate less.

00:09:37.590 --> 00:09:42.010
It's very counterintuitive, but it's true.
How many of you have ever opened up your 401k

00:09:42.010 --> 00:09:46.450
and just gotten overwhelmed with the choices?
Anyone here? Interesting.

00:09:46.450 --> 00:09:50.290
And we're all -- in this room, we've got a
lot of very, very smart people.

00:09:50.290 --> 00:09:53.580
It's not that you're not smart, it's that
it's a human tendency to be overwhelmed by

00:09:53.580 --> 00:09:57.440
too much.
The results of all this information, all this

00:09:57.440 --> 00:10:00.420
media messages is predictable.
It's, we do nothing.

00:10:00.420 --> 00:10:08.470
We say, "We'll do it later."
So, if we know it's important, why don't we

00:10:08.470 --> 00:10:10.850
do it?
One of the biggest things that I talk about

00:10:10.850 --> 00:10:14.750
with 'I will teach you to be rich' is that,
every day we wake up and we're confronted

00:10:14.750 --> 00:10:19.210
with 50 choices we could make about our money.
We can pay off debt. We can earn more.

00:10:19.210 --> 00:10:25.050
We can try to do better at our job.
We can not go out and spend that money on

00:10:25.050 --> 00:10:26.050
lattes.
Whatever it may be.

00:10:26.050 --> 00:10:30.010
Instead, I prefer to focus on the big ones.
Pick the one or two things that actually matter.

00:10:30.010 --> 00:10:34.440
And do those, and let your friends worry about
saving money on diet cokes.

00:10:34.440 --> 00:10:37.580
Let me give you a couple of examples.
This is a simple one.

00:10:37.580 --> 00:10:41.400
You may have seen these numbers before.
Smart Sally starts investing a hundred dollars

00:10:41.400 --> 00:10:44.180
a month at age 25.
She stops at age 35.

00:10:44.180 --> 00:10:48.600
She just lets the money grow.
Dumb Dan doesn't start until he's 35.

00:10:48.600 --> 00:10:51.220
He says, "Oh, I better keep investing till
I retire."

00:10:51.220 --> 00:10:57.910
Both of them at the end -- remember, one person
invested for ten years, another for 30 years.

00:10:57.910 --> 00:11:02.800
Smart Sally has $50,000 more.
So let your friends worry about ordering lattes.

00:11:02.800 --> 00:11:07.070
You could focus on the one or two things that
actually matter.

00:11:07.070 --> 00:11:09.490
Another example.
The difference in having good credit when

00:11:09.490 --> 00:11:13.610
you go to buy a house.
Typical house, let's say, $300,000.

00:11:13.610 --> 00:11:20.880
The difference between having good credit
and poor credit is over $100,000.

00:11:20.880 --> 00:11:26.570
It's not sexy, but it'll make you rich.
So what I want to do now is, get into the

00:11:26.570 --> 00:11:30.850
six weeks.
And I want to talk to you about what you can

00:11:30.850 --> 00:11:33.930
do in six weeks to automate and optimize your
finances.

00:11:33.930 --> 00:11:36.800
Because the No. 1 goal is that no one here
needs to be a financial expert.

00:11:36.800 --> 00:11:39.440
You don't need to be an expert to do this.
You get it set, you get it automated, and

00:11:39.440 --> 00:11:43.550
you get on with your lives.
All right. So here's what we're going to do.

00:11:43.550 --> 00:11:46.790
First, Week One.
I picked Week One as 'credit,' because we

00:11:46.790 --> 00:11:48.810
all have credit cards.
We all hate our credit card companies.

00:11:48.810 --> 00:11:52.071
So, I want to show you how to screw them a
little bit like they screwed some of us.

00:11:52.071 --> 00:11:55.730
There are six commandments.
I'm going to skip the first four, because

00:11:55.730 --> 00:11:57.770
a lot of us know that, but I'm going to talk
to you about the last two.

00:11:57.770 --> 00:12:04.380
They're a little bit counterintuitive.
Who here knows that, when you buy something,

00:12:04.380 --> 00:12:09.870
and let's say, it's got a one-year warrantee.
And your new phone breaks on day 366.

00:12:09.870 --> 00:12:12.360
That's no problem.
Your credit card automatically gives you an

00:12:12.360 --> 00:12:15.360
extra -- it doubles your warrantee up to a
year.

00:12:15.360 --> 00:12:18.880
So if something breaks on day 366, no problem.
Call your credit card; they'll write you a

00:12:18.880 --> 00:12:20.270
check.
It's no problem.

00:12:20.270 --> 00:12:24.430
The other thing that's pretty interesting
that I learned recently was, if you buy something,

00:12:24.430 --> 00:12:29.930
in the first 90 days, it gets stolen, you
break it, or you even lose it, they'll write

00:12:29.930 --> 00:12:33.130
you a check $500 or $1000.
It actually happened to this laptop.

00:12:33.130 --> 00:12:37.740
I bought my first Mac. It was my little baby.
I bought it a few months ago.

00:12:37.740 --> 00:12:41.000
First week, I spilled a huge glass of coffee
on it.

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:44.870
I was almost weeping. And couldn't repair.
It was destroyed.

00:12:44.870 --> 00:12:48.180
And so, I called up the credit card company.
They wrote me a check for 600 bucks.

00:12:48.180 --> 00:12:53.520
I sold it for parts on E-bay and broke even
on my $1400 mistake.

00:12:53.520 --> 00:12:56.591
You can do this with anything -- a sweater
 -- anything.

00:12:56.591 --> 00:13:01.930
Anything you buy with your credit card, okay?
So the point is, you want to use all the benefits

00:13:01.930 --> 00:13:05.180
you get with credit, or with anything for
that matter.

00:13:05.180 --> 00:13:08.190
I was actually going to work at Google as
an APMM.

00:13:08.190 --> 00:13:13.070
And I remember, when they made the offer,
I built my own super-anal, wierdo spreadsheet

00:13:13.070 --> 00:13:16.570
about the benefits that I would get here.
And I think, for me, it was something like

00:13:16.570 --> 00:13:20.300
22 to 26k a year in benefits -- if you use
them.

00:13:20.300 --> 00:13:24.330
You guys know this. Your car insurance.
It's huge discounts.

00:13:24.330 --> 00:13:28.020
Movie tickets, flowers, all kinds of stuff.
Did you know that? These are things you can

00:13:28.020 --> 00:13:32.560
use.
The other thing about credit is to negotiate

00:13:32.560 --> 00:13:35.750
like an Indian, okay?
I have been bred to negotiate like an Indian,

00:13:35.750 --> 00:13:40.930
so I want to share some of this with you.
You can negotiate your car insurance.

00:13:40.930 --> 00:13:45.070
You can negotiate your credit card late fees,
overdraft fees, your gym, cable.

00:13:45.070 --> 00:13:49.050
You can -- even if you carry debt -- you can
negotiate your credit card APR, which if you're

00:13:49.050 --> 00:13:51.600
carrying a lot of debt is a huge win for you,
okay?

00:13:51.600 --> 00:13:54.490
Do you guys want me to do a mock negotiation
right now?

00:13:54.490 --> 00:13:55.490
Would that help?

00:13:55.490 --> 00:13:56.490
A Yes.

00:13:56.490 --> 00:13:59.390
Q All right. So it's easy to say 'just negotiate'
but, for some reason in America, we're scared

00:13:59.390 --> 00:14:01.870
of using the phone.
I don't know why, but people are really afraid

00:14:01.870 --> 00:14:05.460
of using the phone.
Which allows me to No. 1, mock them, but No.

